MENINGITIS, MENINGOCOCCAL - AUSTRALIA: (SOUTH AUSTRALIA) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 23 Sep 2014
Source: The Murray Valley Standard [edited]
http://www.murrayvalleystandard.com.au/story/2575955/meningococcal-rates-rise-in-sa/?cs=12


South Australians (SA) are being reminded to be aware of symptoms of meningococcal disease after an influx of cases were reported to SA Health in recent weeks. So far this year [2014], 20 cases of meningococcal infections have been reported with 8 of those occurring since September.

Chief Public Health Officer Dr Stephen Christley said while the disease was usually rare, numbers increased when more respiratory infections were around. "As we have experienced increased numbers of cases in the past few weeks we're asking the general public to be aware of the symptoms of meningococcal disease and seek medical advice is necessary," he said. "Symptoms of meningococcal infection may include fever, headache, vomiting, stiff neck and sore muscles, followed in some cases by a rash of red and purple spots. Babies or young children with meningococcal infection may also be fretful, refuse feeds or be difficult to wake."

Dr Christley said meningococcal bacteria were carried in the nose and throat of about 10 per cent of the population, but the bacteria were usually harmless. "The bacteria are spread from person to person through close contact, but only a very small number of people develop meningococcal disease," he said. "With all cases of meningococcal infection, SA Health will identify people who may have been in contact with the patient to provide them with information." A Meningococcal Australia spokesperson recommended people keep vaccinations up-to-date and act quickly if they suspected someone had contracted the disease.

"Meningococcal disease, while rare, is a disease that can lead to death in less than 24 hours," the spokesperson said.

"Around 5 to 10 percent of those who contract meningococcal disease will not survive and 20 percent of survivors are left with permanent disabilities that range from learning difficulties, sight or hearing problems, loss of fingers, toes and limbs, and scarring from skin grafts."

