Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Maps of Australia can be seen at http://www.ga.gov.au/image_cache/GA4073.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2799732,286. South Australia is a state in the southern central part of Australia, with a population of 1 650 600 in 2012. A majority of the state's population (77.1 percent) resides within Greater Adelaide's metropolitan area (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Australia).

With 20 cases of meningococcal disease so far this year (2014) in South Australia, the incidence rate is 1.21 per 100 000. However, the news report above fails to tell us the incidence rates in prior years for comparison and we are not told the serogroups involved. We are also not told if any outbreaks of meningococcal disease contributed to the total number of cases in South Australia. (In the US, only about 2 percent of cases of meningococcal disease occurs as part of an outbreak.) Outbreaks can occur in communities, schools, colleges, prisons, and other populations and are usually caused by the same or closely related strains. More information concerning the epidemiological findings concerning the cases of meningococcal disease in South Australia would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

For Australia as a whole, the incidence of meningococcal disease declined from about 700 cases in 2001 to 208 laboratory-confirmed cases in 2012 (incidence rate 0.88 per 100 000), the lowest annual total incidence since surveillance data was collated (http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-cdi3703-pdf-cnt.htm/$FILE/cdi3703e.pdf). The conjugate meningococcal C vaccine was introduced into the National Immunisation Program in 2003. Since 2003, there has been a significant and sustained reduction in serogroup C meningococcal cases from 34 percent of cases in 2003 to 5.7 percent in 2012, accompanied by an increase in serogroup B from 60 percent in 2003 to 83 percent in 2012 (http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-cdi3703-pdf-cnt.htm/$FILE/cdi3703e.pdf).

According to the annual reports of the Australian Meningococcal Surveillance Programme, the number of cases of meningococcal disease in South Australia fluctuated each year, from 13 to 24, of which the percent due to serogroup B ranged from 64 in 2001 to 96 in 2012 (http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-pubs-annlrpt-menganrep.htm).

For comparison, in the US, prior to 2000, an estimated 1400 to 2800 cases of meningococcal disease occurred each year, with an incidence rate of 0.5 to 1.1 per 100 000 population. Since 2000, the incidence of meningococcal disease has decreased (http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/pubs/pinkbook/downloads/mening.pdf). There are now fewer than 1000 cases reported each year (http://www.cdc.gov/meningococcal/surveillance/index.html). - Mod.ML]
